=========================== get translocation sequence

here I use HEK293T-spRY-EMX1 as an example

1. get the supporting reads
$ perl util/find.reads.pl HEK293T-spRY-EMX1.structural.variants ext.pass.cutpoints.gz unc.pass.cutpoints.gz | -k1,1 -k2,2 > zzz

2. get the reads for each loci.
e.g., chr4:46032619--chr8:108187176
chr4:46032619   chr8:108187176  A00808:1380:HV35HDSX5:4:1101:31910:11569#51#-1
chr4:46032619   chr8:108187176  A00808:1380:HV35HDSX5:4:1103:20835:1313#51#231
chr4:46032619   chr8:108187176  A00808:1380:HV35HDSX5:4:1106:30608:29105#51#231
chr4:46032619   chr8:108187176  A00808:1380:HV35HDSX5:4:1107:22046:4100#51#231
chr4:46032619   chr8:108187176  A00808:1380:HV35HDSX5:4:1107:23945:2378#51#-1
chr4:46032619   chr8:108187176  A00808:1380:HV35HDSX5:4:1108:26160:34334#51#-1
chr4:46032619   chr8:108187176  A00808:1380:HV35HDSX5:4:1110:16459:8672#51#231

$ grep -2 A00808:1380:HV35HDSX5:4:1101:31910:11569 *.extendedFrags.fastq

sometimes the data is in uncombined fastq:
grep -2 A00808:1380:HV35HDSX5:4:1101:31910:11569 *.notCombined_*.fastq

3. BLAT the sequence, recognize the spike-in manually as BLAT may contain several basepairs of the spike-in;
as most reads contains mismatches/indels, so I need to use the reference from BLAT


=========================== search for large deletions
$ perl  ../screen.large.deletion.pl HEK293T-spCas9-V2-rep2
